      "question": "Why can naively training an entire neural network in FP16 cause numerical failures?",
      "stem_format": "plain_text",
      "choices_format": "plain_text",
      "choices": [
        "FP16 has less dynamic range and precision, so small values may underflow, large values may overflow, and updates may be rounded too coarsely.",
        "FP16 always changes the mathematical objective, so the model optimizes a different loss function.",
        "FP16 stores gradients exactly but stores activations incorrectly, so only inference is affected.",
        "FP16 fails because it cannot represent negative numbers."
      ],
      "answer_index": 0,
      "explanation": "Reducing precision saves memory, but it also reduces the range and granularity of representable values. That can turn small gradients into zero, large values into invalid numbers, and small updates into no-ops.",
