      "type": "multiple_choice",
      "question": "Why is loss scaling used in FP16 mixed precision training?",
      "stem_format": "plain_text",
      "choices_format": "plain_text",
      "choices": [
        "It makes small gradients larger during backprop so they are less likely to underflow, then the gradients are unscaled before the update.",
        "It makes the model intentionally learn a larger loss to avoid overfitting.",
        "It converts all FP16 tensors back into FP32 before any computation occurs.",
        "It removes the need to compute gradients during backpropagation."
      ],
      "answer_index": 0,
      "explanation": "Many FP16 gradients are too small to represent. Scaling the loss shifts those gradients into a representable range, and unscaling restores the correct update size before applying the optimizer step.",
